04846nam a22007935i 9780271091112DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710911127 a10.1515/97802710911122doi  a(DE-B1597)586188  a(OCoLC)1257324846  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ1090.7.E85bM37 2008eb 7aREL0840002bisacsh04a305.3109409/03122200aMasculinity in the Reformation Era /ced. by Susan C. Karant-Nunn, Scott H. Hendrix. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSixteenth Century Essays & Studies ;v8300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: Deviating from the Norms -- tA Married Man Is a Woman -- tThe Reform of Masculinities in Sixteenth-Century Switzerland -- t"The First Form and Grace" -- tMasculinity and Patriarchy in Reformation Germany -- tPart Two: Civic and Religious Duties -- tFather, Son, and Pious Christian -- tMasculinity and the Reformed Tradition in France -- tRumor, Fear, and Male Civic Duty during a Confessional Crisis -- tPart Three: The Man Martin Luther -- tThe Masculinity of Martin Luther -- t"Lustful Luther" -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThese essays add a unique perspective to studies that reconstruct the identity of manhood in early modern Europe, including France, Switzerland, Spain, and Germany. The authors examine the ways in which sixteenth- and seventeenth-century authorities, both secular and religious, labored to turn boys and men into the Christian males they desired. Topics include disparities among gender paradigms that early modern models prescribed and the tension between the patriarchal model and the civic duties that men were expected to fulfill. Essays about Martin Luther, a prolific self-witness, look into the marriage relationship with its expected and actual gender roles. Contributors to this volume are Scott H. Hendrix, Susan C. Karant-Nunn, Raymond A. Mentzer, Allyson M. Poska, Helmut Puff, Karen E. Spierling, Ulrike Strasser, B. Ann Tlusty, and Merry E. Wiesner-Hanks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMasculinityxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aMasculinityzEuropexHistory. 0aReformationzEurope. 0aSocial change. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh1 aHendrix, Scott H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendrix, Scott H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKarant-Nunn, Susan C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarant-Nunn, Susan C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMentzer, Raymond A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoska, Allyson M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPuff, Helmut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpierling, Karen E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrasser, Ulrike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTlusty, B. Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiesner-Hanks, Merry E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271091112zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271091112423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271091112.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGB